Introduction¶

The stock market is a highly complex and constantly evolving system, making it difficult to accurately predict its movements using traditional methods. In recent years, machine learning models have emerged as a promising alternative for predicting stock prices. The purpose of this research is to explore the effectiveness of various machine learning models in predicting stock prices, with a specific focus on the Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) model and XGboost.

Model Performance¶

In order to compare model on same basis, all models use pre-60 days data to predict close price of next days.

It means I use data since T-60 days to predict close price of T day

I will use last 20% days (almost 1 year) in dataset as testing data.

Because long run performance of machine learning model is not good, I'll test their performance of my simple trading strategies based on the next days predictions.

Simple Trading strategies¶

Assume I own 100 share at the first day of test dataset(20% day) which is 2022-03-22. I will buy stock if the closing price trend is decreasing, and the prediction for the next day's closing price is expected to increase. If the closing price trend is decreasing and the prediction for the next day's closing price is expected to decrease, we will hold our position. If the closing price trend is increasing and the prediction for the next day's closing price is expected to increase, we will continue to hold our position. Finally, if the closing price trend is increasing and the prediction for the next day's closing price is expected to decrease, we will close our position.

We compare the profit earned by model to analyze model short-run performance.

In [329]:
def trading_strategy(test_actually,test_pre):
    prediction_pct = test_pre.pct_change()
    strategy_actually = test_actually # need check previous day pct(see trend)
    strategy_actually_pct = strategy_actually.pct_change()
    start_own_money = 100*strategy_actually[0]
    own_money = start_own_money
    hasMoney = False 
    own_share = 100
    own_worth = start_own_money
    own_money_history = []

    for i in range(len(KO_rm_strategy_actually)-1):
            current_actual_pct = strategy_actually_pct[i]
            current_pre_pct = prediction_pct[i+1]
            if(current_actual_pct<0):
                if(current_pre_pct>0):
                    if(own_money != 0 and i != len(strategy_actually)-2):
                        own_share = own_money/strategy_actually[i] # buy stock
                        own_money = 0
            elif(current_actual_pct>0):
                if(current_pre_pct<0):
                    if(own_money == 0):
                        own_money = own_share*strategy_actually[i] # closing a position
                        own_worth = own_money
                        own_share = 0
            own_money_history.append(own_worth)
            # other condition we keep position
    # buy stock and end and doesn't sell it , so calculate own money use last end close price
    if(own_money == 0):
        own_money = own_share*strategy_actually[len(strategy_actually)-1]
        own_worth = own_money
    own_money_history.append(own_worth)
    profit = own_money-start_own_money
    return profit,own_money_history

# create output y
KO_data_RandomF = KO_data.copy()
KO_data_RandomF["Target"] = KO_data["Close"].shift(-1)

KO_rf_test_len = len(KO_data_RandomF)-int(np.floor(len(KO_data)*0.8))
# use pre-60 days data, create extra 240 features which include pre-60 days data
# create lagged features
close_lag_cols = [f"Close Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]
open_lag_cols = [f"Open Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]
high_lag_cols = [f"High Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]
low_lag_cols = [f"Low Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]

close_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["Close"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)
open_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["Open"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)
high_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["High"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)
low_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["Low"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)

close_lag_df.columns = close_lag_cols
open_lag_df.columns = open_lag_cols
high_lag_df.columns = high_lag_cols
low_lag_df.columns = low_lag_cols

KO_data_RandomF = pd.concat([KO_data_RandomF, close_lag_df, open_lag_df, high_lag_df, low_lag_df], axis=1)
# drop missing row, which means drop first 60 data
KO_data_RandomF.dropna(inplace=True)

# training data don't require irrelevant feature and data on the predict day
KO_data_RandomF_X = KO_data_RandomF.drop(["Open", "High", "Low", "Close","Adj Close", "Volume", "MA", "Target"],axis=1)
KO_data_RandomF_Y = KO_data_RandomF["Target"]

# split train and test dataset
KO_data_RandomF_X_v = KO_data_RandomF_X.values
KO_data_RandomF_y_v = KO_data_RandomF_Y.values
KO_new_train_len = len(KO_data_RandomF_X)-KO_rf_test_len
# keep all model use 266 test size
KO_RF_X_train = KO_data_RandomF_X_v[:KO_new_train_len,:]
KO_RF_X_test = KO_data_RandomF_X_v[KO_new_train_len:,:]
KO_RF_y_train = KO_data_RandomF_y_v[:KO_new_train_len]
KO_RF_y_test = KO_data_RandomF_y_v[KO_new_train_len:]

ko_forest = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100,max_depth=20, random_state=40).fit(KO_RF_X_train,KO_RF_y_train)
KO_train_pred = ko_forest.predict(KO_RF_X_train)
KO_test_pred = ko_forest.predict(KO_RF_X_test)
KO_train_mse = mean_squared_error(KO_RF_y_train,KO_train_pred)
KO_test_mse = mean_squared_error(KO_RF_y_test,KO_test_pred)

# first create Prediction column
KO_data_RandomF_training = KO_data_RandomF_X[:KO_new_train_len].copy()
KO_data_RandomF_testing = KO_data_RandomF_X[KO_new_train_len:].copy()
KO_data_RandomF_training["Prediction"] = KO_train_pred
KO_data_RandomF_testing["Prediction"] = KO_test_pred

Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM)¶

LSTM (Long Short-Term Memory) is a type of recurrent neural network (RNN) that is capable of processing sequential data with a memory cell that can selectively remember or forget previous inputs.

The ability of LSTMs to capture long-term dependencies in time series data (like stock data) is nice, so I think it has good performance on predicting stock prices.

I need first handle the dataset to make it fit the input for LSTM. It's similar to my handle in random forest, pre-60 days data per for one target close price.

In [267]:
KO_data_lstm = KO_data.copy()
# only need those 4 features
KO_data_lstm_X = KO_data_lstm.filter(["Close","Open","High","Low"])
# KO_data_lstm_X = KO_data_lstm.filter(["Close"])

# use scaler handle to dataset first
# separate use scaler for input and output
KO_lstm_scaler = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0,1))

XG Boosting¶

It's ensemble learning method that combine multiple weak models to create a strong predictive model.

If we update the training set so that it always keep all data of days before predicted day (tomorrow), then XG Boosting perform perfect

Add T day of test data to train set in order to predict T+1 days

I have 266 test sample, so the model will re-train 266 times (honestly it make the profit decrease a lot as I test, so I re-do a non-retrain version for Coca Cola)

In [408]:
# create output y
KO_data_XGF = KO_data.copy()
KO_data_XGF["Target"] = KO_data["Close"].shift(-1)

KO_XG_test_len = len(KO_data_XGF)-int(np.floor(len(KO_data)*0.8))
# use pre-60 days data, create extra 240 features which include pre-60 days data
# create lagged features
close_lag_cols = [f"Close Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]
open_lag_cols = [f"Open Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]
high_lag_cols = [f"High Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]
low_lag_cols = [f"Low Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]

close_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["Close"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)
open_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["Open"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)
high_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["High"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)
low_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["Low"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)

close_lag_df.columns = close_lag_cols
open_lag_df.columns = open_lag_cols
high_lag_df.columns = high_lag_cols
low_lag_df.columns = low_lag_cols

KO_data_XGF = pd.concat([KO_data_XGF, close_lag_df, open_lag_df, high_lag_df, low_lag_df], axis=1)
# drop missing row, which means drop first 60 data
KO_data_XGF.dropna(inplace=True)

# training data don't require irrelevant feature and data on the predict day
KO_data_XGF_X = KO_data_XGF.drop(["Open", "High", "Low", "Close","Adj Close", "Volume", "MA", "Target"],axis=1)
KO_data_XGF_Y = KO_data_XGF["Target"]

# split train and test dataset
KO_data_XGF_X_v = KO_data_XGF_X.values
KO_data_XGF_y_v = KO_data_XGF_Y.values
KO_new_train_len = len(KO_data_XGF_X)-KO_XG_test_len
# keep all model use 266 test size
KO_XG_X_train = KO_data_XGF_X_v[:KO_new_train_len,:]
KO_XG_X_test = KO_data_XGF_X_v[KO_new_train_len:,:]
KO_XG_y_train = KO_data_XGF_y_v[:KO_new_train_len]
KO_XG_y_test = KO_data_XGF_y_v[KO_new_train_len:]
KO_XG_y_copy = KO_XG_y_train.copy()
# re-train the model after it add a test sample of new day
KO_XG_test_pred = []
for i in range(len(KO_XG_y_test)):
    ko_Boost = XGBRegressor(n_estimators=100,max_depth=20,learning_rate=0.4,min_child_weight=4).fit(KO_XG_X_train,KO_XG_y_train)
    if(i==0):
        KO_XG_train_pred = ko_Boost.predict(KO_XG_X_train) # only predict train data once
    KO_XG_test_pred_one = ko_Boost.predict(KO_XG_X_test[i].reshape(1,-1))
    KO_XG_test_pred.append(KO_XG_test_pred_one)
    # add i day of test data to train set in order to predict i+1 days
    # update train set
    KO_XG_X_train = np.vstack((KO_XG_X_train,KO_XG_X_test[i].reshape(1,-1)))
    KO_XG_y_train = np.append(KO_XG_y_train,KO_XG_y_test[i])

# first create Prediction column
KO_train_mse = mean_squared_error(KO_XG_y_copy,KO_XG_train_pred)
KO_test_mse = mean_squared_error(KO_XG_y_test,KO_XG_test_pred)
KO_data_XGF_training = KO_data_XGF_X[:KO_new_train_len].copy()
KO_data_XGF_testing = KO_data_XGF_X[KO_new_train_len:].copy()
KO_data_XGF_training["Prediction"] = KO_XG_train_pred
KO_data_XGF_testing["Prediction"] = KO_XG_test_pred
# plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))
ax.plot(KO_data_XGF_Y, label='Coca-Cola actual close price',linewidth=1.5)
ax.plot(KO_data_XGF_training["Prediction"], label='Coca-Cola train prediction',linewidth=1.5)
ax.plot(KO_data_XGF_testing["Prediction"], label='Coca-Cola test prediction',linewidth=1.5)
ax.set_title("Coca-Cola XG Boost",fontsize = 15)
ax.set_xlabel('Date',fontsize = 15)
ax.set_ylabel('Price',fontsize = 15)
ax.legend()
ax.grid()
fig.set_facecolor((0.96, 0.96, 0.96))
plt.show()
print(f"MSE of XG Boost on training data {KO_train_mse}")
print(f"MSE of XG Boost on testing data {KO_test_mse}")

KO_data_XGF["Target"] = KO_data["Close"].shift(-1)

KO_XG_test_len = len(KO_data_XGF)-int(np.floor(len(KO_data)*0.8))
# use pre-60 days data, create extra 240 features which include pre-60 days data
# create lagged features
close_lag_cols = [f"Close Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]
open_lag_cols = [f"Open Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]
high_lag_cols = [f"High Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]
low_lag_cols = [f"Low Lag {i}" for i in range(1, 61)]

close_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["Close"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)
open_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["Open"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)
high_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["High"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)
low_lag_df = pd.concat([KO_data["Low"].shift(i) for i in range(1, 61)], axis=1)

close_lag_df.columns = close_lag_cols
open_lag_df.columns = open_lag_cols
high_lag_df.columns = high_lag_cols
low_lag_df.columns = low_lag_cols

KO_data_XGF = pd.concat([KO_data_XGF, close_lag_df, open_lag_df, high_lag_df, low_lag_df], axis=1)
# drop missing row, which means drop first 60 data
KO_data_XGF.dropna(inplace=True)

# training data don't require irrelevant feature and data on the predict day
KO_data_XGF_X = KO_data_XGF.drop(["Open", "High", "Low", "Close","Adj Close", "Volume", "MA", "Target"],axis=1)
KO_data_XGF_Y = KO_data_XGF["Target"]

# split train and test dataset
KO_data_XGF_X_v = KO_data_XGF_X.values
KO_data_XGF_y_v = KO_data_XGF_Y.values
KO_new_train_len = len(KO_data_XGF_X)-KO_XG_test_len
# keep all model use 266 test size
KO_XG_X_train = KO_data_XGF_X_v[:KO_new_train_len,:]
KO_XG_X_test = KO_data_XGF_X_v[KO_new_train_len:,:]
KO_XG_y_train = KO_data_XGF_y_v[:KO_new_train_len]
KO_XG_y_test = KO_data_XGF_y_v[KO_new_train_len:]

ko_Boost = XGBRegressor(n_estimators=100,max_depth=20,learning_rate=0.4,min_child_weight=4).fit(KO_XG_X_train,KO_XG_y_train)
  
KO_XG_train_pred = ko_Boost.predict(KO_XG_X_train) # only predict train data once
KO_XG_test_pred = ko_Boost.predict(KO_XG_X_test)

# first create Prediction column
KO_train_mse = mean_squared_error(KO_XG_y_train,KO_XG_train_pred)
KO_test_mse = mean_squared_error(KO_XG_y_test,KO_XG_test_pred)
KO_data_XGF_training = KO_data_XGF_X[:KO_new_train_len].copy()
KO_data_XGF_testing = KO_data_XGF_X[KO_new_train_len:].copy()
KO_data_XGF_training["Prediction"] = KO_XG_train_pred
KO_data_XGF_testing["Prediction"] = KO_XG_test_pred
# plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 8))
ax.plot(KO_data_XGF_Y, label='Coca-Cola actual close price',linewidth=1.5)
ax.plot(KO_data_XGF_training["Prediction"], label='Coca-Cola train prediction',linewidth=1.5)
ax.plot(KO_data_XGF_testing["Prediction"], label='Coca-Cola test prediction',linewidth=1.5)
ax.set_title("Coca-Cola XG Boost",fontsize = 15)
ax.set_xlabel('Date',fontsize = 15)
ax.set_ylabel('Price',fontsize = 15)
ax.legend()
ax.grid()
fig.set_facecolor((0.96, 0.96, 0.96))
plt.show()
print(f"MSE of XG Boost on training data {KO_train_mse}")
print(f"MSE of XG Boost on testing data {KO_test_mse}")
